B13 FRAMBOISE D’ALSACE (Estate of Hess). . . . . .. 12.95 147.00

During the slow season in his orchard, Alfred Hess followed the practice of sending his field workers by truck up the Vosges Mountains to an altitude above 1500 feet to gather wild raspberries for his Framboise. A truck load of men and a day’s picking will yield very few bottles because it takes 15 quarts of wild raspberries to make one bottle of Framboise. The price is not cheap—a good one costs this much in

France—but it is worth it to those who appreciate the great delicacy and finesse of this remarkable distillate, colorless to the eye, but a rainbow of flavor to the taste buds.
